🔗 URL Shortener – System Design (Interview Ready)
A URL shortener (like Bitly or TinyURL) converts long URLs into short, unique links.

Example:
https://example.com/products/category/12345 → https://sho.rt/Ab3Xk

1️⃣ Functional Requirements
✅ Core Features
    Generate short URL from long URL
    Redirect short URL → original long URL
    Custom alias support (optional)
    Set expiration time (optional)
    Track analytics (clicks, location, device)

❌ Non-Functional Requirements
      Highly available (99.99%)
      Low latency redirection (< 100ms)
      Scalable (billions of URLs)
      Secure (prevent spam/malware)

2️⃣ High-Level Design (HLD)
🔹 Components
    1->Client
      Browser / Mobile App
    2->Load Balancer
      Distributes traffic
    3->Application Servers
      -Handle:
        URL creation
        Redirect requests
    4->Database
      Stores mapping:
      short_code → long_url
    5->Cache (Redis)
      Fast lookup for frequently accessed URLs
    6-> Analytics Service
      Async event logging via queue (Kafka)

3️⃣ Deep Dive – Key Design Decisions
🔹 A. How to Generate Short Code?
Option 1: Hashing (MD5/SHA)
    Hash long URL → take first 6-8 characters
    
    Problem: collisions

Option 2: Base62 Encoding (Recommended)
Characters:

    a-z (26)
    A-Z (26)
    0-9 (10)
    Total = 62
    If ID = 125 → Base62 → "cb"
    If length = 7
    Possible combinations = 62⁷ ≈ 3.5 trillion URLs
  
    How it works:
    Generate auto-increment ID  
    Convert to Base62
    Store mapping

🔹 B. Database Design
    Table: URL
    Column	Type
    id	bigint (PK)
    short_code	varchar(10) UNIQUE
    long_url	text
    created_at	timestamp
    expiry_date	timestamp
    user_id	bigint
    click_count	bigint
      Index on:
      short_code (critical)

🔹 C. Redirect Flow
    User hits:
    https://sho.rt/Ab3Xk
    Steps:
      1->Load Balancer
      2->App server
      3->Check Redis cache
      4->If hit → redirect
      5->If miss → DB lookup → update cache → redirect

🔹 D. Scaling Strategy
  🔹 Read Heavy System
      Redirection is 1000x more frequent than creation.
      
      Scaling Plan:
      Problem	Solution
      High traffic	Horizontal scaling
      DB overload	Read replicas
      Slow lookup	Redis cache
      Analytics load	Async queue (Kafka)
      Global users	CDN + Geo DNS

🔹 E. Handling Collisions
      If using random generation:
      Check DB before insert
      Retry if exists
      If using Base62 + unique ID:
      No collision issue

🔹 F. Prevent Abuse
      Rate limiting
      CAPTCHA
      Blacklist malicious domains
      Expiry for inactive URLs

4️⃣ Capacity Estimation (Interview Style)
      Assume:
      100M new URLs per month
      1B redirects per month
      Storage:
      1 URL record ≈ 500 bytes
      100M × 500B = 50GB per month
      600GB per year
      
      Use:
      Partitioning by ID or date

5️⃣ Advanced Optimizations
    🔹 1. Pre-generate Short Codes
    Keep pool of unused codes.
    
    🔹 2. Bloom Filter
    Check existence quickly before DB hit.
    
    🔹 3. Multi-Region Setup
    Use Geo DNS
    
    Replicate DB globally
    Keep regional caches

6️⃣ LLD (Low-Level Design)
    Classes
    URLService
      - createShortURL()
      - getLongURL()
    
    URLRepository
      - save()
      - findByShortCode()
    
    CacheService
      - get()
      - set()
7️⃣ Interview 5-Minute Script (Memorize This)
"I would design the URL shortener as a highly available read-heavy system.
The core idea is mapping short_code to long_url stored in a distributed database.
For short code generation, I would use auto-increment ID + Base62 encoding to avoid collisions.
Since redirection traffic is very high, I would use Redis cache to reduce DB load.
For scalability, I would use load balancers, read replicas, and horizontal scaling.
Analytics would be processed asynchronously via Kafka to avoid impacting redirect latency."

