===================================“What are the edge cases in this design?”===================================

Below is a complete FAANG-level edge case checklist for URL Shortener.

🔥 1️⃣ Functional Edge Cases
🔹 1. Same URL submitted multiple times
Problem:
User shortens the same long URL repeatedly.

Solution:
Maintain reverse mapping (long_url → short_code)
Return existing short code

🔹 2. Custom alias collision
User wants:
short.ly/google
But it already exists.
Solution:
DB UNIQUE constraint on short_code
Return error: “Alias already taken”

🔹 3. Expired URL accessed
If URL expired:
Return 410 Gone
Or show custom expiration page

🔹 4. Invalid URL input
Examples:
Missing protocol
Malformed string
Very long URL (10,000+ chars)

Solution:
Validate format
Set max length limit (e.g., 2048 chars)

🔹 5. Extremely long short code request
If someone tries:
short.ly/aaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaa
Solution:
Enforce fixed-length code validation
Reject invalid patterns early

🔥 2️⃣ Performance Edge Cases
🔹 6. Hot URL (Viral Traffic)
One link gets millions of hits per second.

Risks:
Redis overload
Single DB shard overload
Mitigation:
CDN caching
Redis replication
Consistent hashing
Request coalescing

🔹 7. Cache Stampede
Cache entry expires → thousands of requests hit DB simultaneously.

Solution:
Distributed lock
Request coalescing
Slight TTL randomization (jitter)

🔹 8. Cache Memory Full
Redis runs out of memory.

Solution:
LRU eviction
Scale Redis cluster
Monitor memory thresholds

🔥 3️⃣ Distributed System Edge Cases
🔹 9. ID collision
If using random generation:
Collision risk increases
Solution:
Snowflake-style ID
DB uniqueness constraint

🔹 🔟 Clock skew in distributed ID generation
If using timestamp-based ID:
Servers with wrong clock may create duplicate IDs
Solution:
NTP sync
Logical clock fallback
Use sequence bits carefully

🔹 1️⃣1️⃣ DB shard becomes hot
If sharding by sequential ID:
One shard receives most traffic
Solution:
Hash-based sharding
Consistent hashing

🔹 1️⃣2️⃣ Redis crash
Cache unavailable.
System behavior:
Fallback to DB
Gradual cache rebuild

🔹 1️⃣3️⃣ DB failure
Primary DB crashes.
Solution:
Primary-replica setup
Automatic failover

🔹 1️⃣4️⃣ Region failure
Entire data center goes down.

Solution:
Multi-region deployment
Geo DNS routing
Cross-region replication

🔥 4️⃣ Security & Abuse Edge Cases
🔹 1️⃣5️⃣ Brute-force short code guessing
Attackers try:

short.ly/aaaaaa
short.ly/aaaaba
Solution:
Rate limiting
Use longer short codes (6–8 chars)
Monitor suspicious patterns

🔹 1️⃣6️⃣ Spam URL generation
Bot creates millions of short URLs.

Solution:
Rate limiting per IP/user
CAPTCHA
API key authentication

🔹 1️⃣7️⃣ Malicious redirect links
Phishing links.

Solution:
Blacklist known domains
URL scanning service
Abuse reporting system

🔹 1️⃣8️⃣ Open redirect vulnerability
Ensure system only redirects stored URLs.
Never accept arbitrary redirect parameters.

🔥 5️⃣ Data Growth Edge Cases
🔹 1️⃣9️⃣ Database storage explosion
If storing 100M URLs/day:

DB grows rapidly
Solution:
Sharding
Archival storage
Delete expired URLs

🔹 2️⃣0️⃣ Click count overflow
If click count exceeds integer limit.

Solution:
Use BIGINT
Async aggregation

🔥 6️⃣ Business Logic Edge Cases
🔹 2️⃣1️⃣ URL updated after creation
    If original URL changes:
    Should we allow editing?
    If yes:
    Update DB
    Invalidate cache

🔹 2️⃣2️⃣ Same URL, different users
    Should each user get unique short code?
    Design choice:
    Global dedup OR user-specific mapping
    Clarify requirement in interview.

🔹 2️⃣3️⃣ Private URLs
    If user wants:
    Only accessible to logged-in users
    Requires:
    Auth layer
    Access control

🔥 7️⃣ Observability Edge Cases
🔹 2️⃣4️⃣ Silent performance degradation
    If cache hit rate drops:
    DB overload risk
    Monitor:
    Cache hit %
    P99 latency

🔹 2️⃣5️⃣ Traffic spikes (Black Friday)
    Auto-scale:
    App servers
    Redis cluster
    DB replicas

